'''Jesús Daniel Gallardo Vasconcelos''' (born 15 August 1994) is a Mexican professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left-back]] or [[Midfielder#Winger|left-winger]] for [[Liga MX]] club [[Toluca FC|Toluca]] and the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]].

After passing through the youth academies of [[Once Hermanos]], [[Jaguares de la 48]], and [[Pumas UNAM (youth)|UNAM]], Gallardo made his debut for the senior [[Pumas UNAM|UNAM]] team in 2014. Scoring 11 goals in 82 appearances, he departed the club for [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]] in 2018. During his tenure with ''Los Rayados'', Gallardo won one [[Liga MX|league]] title, one [[Copa MX]] title, and two [[CONCACAF Champions Cup]] titles, while making over 200 appearances and scoring 21 goals for the club. Since joining Toluca in 2024, Gallardo has won one league title.

Gallardo made his debut for Mexico in October 2016 in a friendly against [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]]. He was part of Mexico's squads at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]. He was also involved in the squads that won the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2019]], [[2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2023]], and [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], as well as the [[2024–25 CONCACAF Nations League]].

==Club career==
===Youth===
Gallardo began his career at 15 years old with [[Once Hermanos]] from 2009,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jesús Gallardo: 5 años de Primera|url=https://www.tabascohoy.com/nota/494980/cumple-jesus-gallardo-5-anos-de-primera-division|work=Tabasco Hoy|first=Mauricio|last=Valencia|date=26 November 2019|language=es|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref> until making the switch to [[Jaguares de la 48]] in 2011,<ref name="Descubriendo">{{cite web|title=Descubriendo a Gallardo|first=Rubén|last=Guerrero Atilano|url=https://www.milenio.com/deportes/descubriendo-a-gallardo|work=Milenio|date=4 October 2016|language=es|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref> and ultimately getting the attention of first division team [[Pumas UNAM]]. From there, in 2013,<ref name="Descubriendo"/> he joined Pumas UNAM youth academy, successfully going through the U-20 team and [[Pumas Morelos]].

===UNAM===
In 2014, Gallardo was eventually promoted to the first team by coach [[Guillermo Vázquez (footballer)|Guillermo Vázquez]].<ref name="Descubriendo"/> Gallardo scored his first goal with UNAM in a [[Copa MX]] group stage match against [[Toluca FC|Toluca]] on 16 September 2014 that marked his debut with the jersey that ended 2–2 but didn't make his competitive league debut in [[Liga MX]] until 23 November 2014 which ended in a 4–2 win against [[C.F. Monterrey|Monterrey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tabascohoy.com/nota/337841/jesus-gallardo-un-tabasqueno-con-piel-felina |title=Jesús Gallardo, un tabasceño con piel felina |publisher= Luis Chavez Jr. |website= Tabascohoy.com|date=13 July 2016 |access-date= 2026-05-29}}</ref>

On 21 November 2016, he would score a brace against [[W Connection F.C.|W Connection]] during the [[2016–17 CONCACAF Champions League group stage]] that ended 8–1.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pumas UNAM 8–1 W Connection FC|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/match?gameId=457202|work=ESPN|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref>

On 9 August 2017, during an [[Apertura 2017 Copa MX]] group stage match against Monterrey, he would score the tying goal during stoppage time, leaving the match 1–1.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pumas le roba un punto al Monterrey en la Copa MX|url=https://mexico.as.com/mexico/2017/08/10/futbol/1502336721_662179.html|website=Mexico.as.com|publisher=AS|language=es|date=9 August 2017|access-date=22 October 2018}}</ref>

===Monterrey===
====2018–19: Debut season, Copa MX, and first CONCACAF Champions League title====
On 29 May 2018, Gallardo joined Monterrey.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico international winger Jesus Gallardo swaps Pumas for Monterrey|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/3513082/mexico-international-winger-jesus-gallardo-swaps-pumas-for-monterrey|work=ESPN|first=Tom|last=Marshall|date=29 May 2018|access-date=18 September 2018}}</ref> He would make his debut with the team on 21 July 2018 as a starter against [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]], winning 1–0.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pachuca 0–1 Monterrey|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/match?gameId=517051|work=ESPN|access-date=20 September 2018}}</ref> On 29 September, he would score his first goal with Monterrey, scoring on the 74th minute in a 3–0 win over [[Club Tijuana|Tijuana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Rayados le bastó menos de 90' y una tormenta para golear a Xolos|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/2018/09/29/a-rayados-le-basto-menos-de-90-y-una-tormenta-para-golear-a-xolos|first=Sahid|last=Hernández Rosete|date=29 September 2018|access-date=1 October 2018|language=es}}</ref> On 20 October, in a league match against [[Toluca FC|Toluca]], he scored the tying goal at the 73rd minute in which Monterrey would later go on to win 2–1.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Monterrey vs Toluca: Rayados remonta en casa para vencer al Toluca - MARCA Claro México |url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol/liga-mx/2018/10/21/5bcbfab122601d003d8b45c3.html |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190410052954/https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol/liga-mx/2018/10/21/5bcbfab122601d003d8b45c3.html |archive-date=2019-04-10 |access-date=2026-05-29 |work=MARCA Claro México |language=es-MX}}</ref>

On 23 October he scored the decisive penalty in the shootout of the [[Apertura 2018 Copa MX]] semi-finals against Pachuca, sending his team to the [[Apertura 2018 Copa MX Final|final]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/2018/10/23/rayados-avanza-a-final-de-copa-mx-tras-derrotar-a-tuzos-en-penales|title=Rayados avanza a Final de Copa MX tras derrotar a Tuzos en penales|work=MedioTiempo|access-date=24 October 2018|language=es-MX}}</ref> On 3 November he provided an assist and scored a goal in Monterrey's 2–0 victory over [[C.D. Veracruz|Veracruz]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Los tres grandes refuerzos dieron los tres puntos|url=https://www.multimedios.com/deportes/liga-mx/los-tres-grandes-refuerzos-dieron-los-tres-puntos|website=Multimedios.com|publisher=Multimedios Televisión|first=Eduardo|last=Torres|date=5 November 2018|access-date=6 November 2018|language=es}}</ref>

As Monterrey won the [[2019 CONCACAF Champions League Finals]] against [[Clásico Regiomontano|crosstown rivals]] [[Tigres UANL]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Rayados vanquish frustration of previous Final Regia loss with Concacaf Champions League victory|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/rayados-vanquish-frustration-of-previous-final-regia-loss/g5fh6dfy2t9z1u9kvqq7l9dz3|work=Goal.com|first=Jon|last=Arnold|date=2 May 2019|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref> he was included in the Team of the Tournament.<ref name="TotT">{{cite tweet |author=Scotiabank Concacaf Champions League|user=TheChampions |number=1124021294750732288 |title=Presenting the Scotiabank Concacaf Champions League 2019 Team of the Tournament!|date=2 May 2019 |access-date=2 May 2019}}</ref>

====2019–20: First league title and ''El Triplete''====
At the end of the December, he would win the [[Apertura 2019 Liga MX championship stage|Apertura championship]] finals against [[Club América|América]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Monterrey defeat Club America on penalties to win Liga MX 2019 Apertura title|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=560779|work=ESPN|first=Tom|last=Marshall|date=30 December 2019|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref>

With Monterrey's victory of the [[2019–20 Copa MX]], they had obtained the [[Treble (association football)|continental treble]].<ref>{{cite web|title=¡TRI-PLE-TE! {{!}} Rayados consiguió triplete y ahora va por el campeonato del Guard1anes 2020|url=https://www.90min.com/es/posts/tri-ple-te-rayados-consiguio-triplete-y-ahora-va-por-el-campeonato-del-guard1anes-2020|work=90 Min|language=es|date=5 November 2020|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref>

===Toluca===
On 5 June 2024, Gallardo was confirmed to have signed with [[Toluca FC|Toluca]] for $5 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mexico/nota/_/id/13751291/toluca-jesus-gallardo-fichajes-liga-mx-apertura-2024|title=Toluca cerro fichaje de Jesús Gallardo, aseguran fuentes|work=ESPN Deportes|date=5 June 2024|accessdate=13 June 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
===2016–17: Beginnings and first CONCACAF Gold Cup===
Gallardo received his first call up to the [[Mexico national football team|senior national team]] to replace the injured [[Ángel Sepúlveda]] for matches against [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] and [[Panama national football team|Panama]] in October 2016,<ref>{{cite news|title=De Pumas al Tri; Jesús Gallardo, convocado por Osorio |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/2016/10/02/de-pumas-al-tri-jesus-gallardo-convocado-por-osorio |access-date=5 October 2016|publisher=mediotiempo.com|date=2 October 2016}}</ref> making his international debut on the 8th of the month as a starter against New Zealand in a 2–1 victory, contributing a crucial pass for the winning goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Discreto debut de Jesús Gallardo con la Selección|url=https://www.vavel.com/mx/futbol-mexicano/2016/10/09/pumas/705388-discreto-debut-de-jesus-gallardo-con-la-seleccion.html|work=Vavel|first=Andrés|last=Ocampo|date=8 October 2016|access-date=10 October 2018}}</ref>

On 28 June 2017, Gallardo was called up to participate in the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Lista la convocatoria de México para la Copa Oro|url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol/copa-oro/2017/06/29/59542cb0ca4741ab508b4609.html|work=Marca|date=28 June 2017|access-date=10 October 2018}}</ref> managing to appear in all games until their 1–0 semi-final loss against [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]].

===2018–2019: First FIFA World Cup and second CONCACAF Gold Cup===
[[File:Ger-Mex (14).jpg|thumb|Gallardo celebrating following Mexico's 1–0 win over [[Germany national football team|Germany]] during the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]]]]

In May 2018, Gallardo was named in Mexico's preliminary 28-man [[Mexico national football team|squad]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad - Final 23-man lists|access-date=2026-05-29|website=Goal.com}}</ref> and in June, was ultimately included in the final 23-man roster.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Down |first=Aisha |date=2026-05-29 |title=vin88 |url=https://vin88.wtf |access-date=2026-05-29 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Convocatoria de la Selección Nacional de México |url=https://miseleccion.mx/convocatoria-la-seleccion-nacional-mexico-13/ |website=MiSeleccion.mx |language=es |access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref> 

During Mexico's final group stage match against Sweden, he received a [[yellow card (association football)|yellow card]] in the 13th second of the match for his elbow contact made with [[Ola Toivonen]]'s face, marking it as the fastest yellow card given in [[FIFA World Cup]] history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jesus Gallardo's yellow card for Mexico fastest in World Cup history|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/mexico/story/3547297/jesus-gallardos-yellow-card-for-mexico-fastest-in-world-cup-history|work=ESPN|date=27 June 2018 |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> He went on to play as a starter in all of the group stage matches, including the [[2018 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Brazil vs Mexico|round-of-16 loss]] against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref name="fifa">{{cite web|title=Jesus GALLARDO|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player/402772/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623113448/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player/402772/|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 June 2018|work=FIFA|access-date=22 October 2018}}</ref> 

He was included in [[Gerardo Martino]]'s preliminary roster for the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Marco Fabián vuelve y no está Tecatito; anuncian lista previa de México para Copa Oro|url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/seleccion-mayor/seleccion-mexicana-prelista-copa-oro-2019-tata-martino|publisher=Mediotiempo.com|first=Enrique|last=Martínez Villar|date=14 May 2019|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref> and was eventually in the final list.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://miseleccion.mx/noticias/2560/Convocatoria-Final-para-Copa-Oro-2019|title=Convocatoria Final para Copa Oro 2019|website=MiSeleccion.mx|publisher=Mexican Football Federation|date=5 June 2019|language=es|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref> He appeared in all matches of the tournament, as Mexico defeated the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup Final|final]].<ref name="Straus">{{cite web|title=Mexico Turns Tide, Wins Gold Cup Title Again vs. Wasteful USMNT|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/07/07/mexico-usa-gold-cup-title-dos-santos-pizarro-pulisic-berhalter|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|first=Brian|last=Straus|date=7 July 2019|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref> He was listed in the tournament's Best XI.<ref name="2019 CGC XI">{{cite web|url=https://www.goldcup.org/en/awards/2019-concacaf-gold-cup-best-xi|title=2019 Concacaf Gold Cup - Best XI|website=goldcup.org|date=7 July 2019|access-date=8 July 2019|archive-date=30 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730113130/https://www.goldcup.org/en/awards/2019-concacaf-gold-cup-best-xi|url-status=dead}}</ref> Following the victory, Martino declared Gallardo to be the best player of the match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Para Martino, Jesús Gallardo fue el mejor jugador del partido|url=https://www.goal.com/es/noticias/para-martino-jesus-gallardo-fue-el-mejor-jugador-del-partido/1e1gj9z9a4i1b16lzmve8fgang|website=Goal.com|language=es|date=8 July 2019|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref>

===2022–2024: Second FIFA World Cup and 100th cap===
[[File:Argentina vs mexico messi vs jesusgallardo (cropped).jpg|thumb|Gallardo facing-off [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]'s [[Lionel Messi]] during the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]]]]
In October 2022, Gallardo was named in Mexico's preliminary 31-man [[Mexico national football team|squad]] for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], and in November, was ultimately included in the final 26-man roster.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lista de convocados de la Selección Mexicana al Mundial de Qatar 2022|url=https://www.tvazteca.com/aztecadeportes/lista-oficial-convocados-seleccion-mexicana-mundial-qatar-2022|work=Tvazteca.com|first=Omar|last=Moro|date=14 November 2022|language=Spanish|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref>

On 7 September 2024, he played his 100th international match, according to the [[Mexican Football Federation]], in a 3–0 friendly win over [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://esto.com.mx/844000-jesus-gallardo-celebra-100-partidos-con-la-camiseta-de-la-seleccion-mexicana/ |title=Jesús Gallardo celebra 100 partidos con la camiseta de la Selección: "Es un logro para mi Carrera" |publisher=esto.com |language=es |date=7 September 2024 |access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Gallardo is known for intensity, pace, and physical strength, allowing him to be both dangerous and intense during a whole match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Talent Radar: CONCACAF Gold Cup 2017 U-23 Team of the Tournament |url=http://outsideoftheboot.com/2017/07/30/talent-radar-concacaf-gold-cup-2017-u-23-team-of-the-tournament/|work=Outsideoftheboot.com|first=Jose Miguel |last=Saraiva |access-date=20 September 2018}}</ref><ref name="ESPN"/> [[FIFA]] described him as "Gallardo's many assets include his speed, ability to take people on and his selfless distribution. A regular source of assists and the archetypal team player, he is adept at pressing high up the pitch and catching opponents out of position."<ref name="fifa"/>

Starting off as a [[Midfielder#Winger|left-winger]] on the club level, former Mexico national team coach [[Juan Carlos Osorio]] used him on a more defensive position as [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left-back]].<ref name="Goal.com">{{cite web|title=Pumas winger Jesus Gallardo continues making Mexico case|url=http://www.goal.com/en-qa/news/pumas-winger-jesus-gallardo-continues-making-mexico-national/1bwo35onr3x961vwqvjzxx42hb|work=Goal.com|first=Jon|last=Arnold|date=21 January 2018|access-date=20 September 2018}}</ref><ref name="ESPN">{{cite web|title=Jesus Gallardo's versatility could earn him a place in Mexico's World Cup squad|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/mexican-liga-mx/22/blog/post/3351545/jesus-gallardos-versatility-could-earn-him-a-place-in-mexicos-world-cup-squad|work=ESPN|first=Nayib|last=Moran|date=17 January 2018|access-date=20 September 2018}}</ref> With the arrival of new national team coach Gerardo Martino, he chose to keep him as a left-back.<ref>{{cite web|title=Martino finds ideal fullbacks for his system in Gallardo, Rodriguez|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/martino-finds-ideal-fullbacks-for-his-system-in-gallardo/94ddw73eeub71xxddotp0kzkt|work=Goal.com|first=Jon|last=Arnold|date=28 June 2019|access-date=2026-05-29}}</ref>

